definitions.definition: From one side of something to the other.

examples: I didn't like the look of the place, so I drove through without stopping.
I opened the window and climbed through .

subdefinitions.definition: So as to overcome an obstacle and pass beyond it; past .
examples: The road is blocked by an overturned truck, and cars can't get through .
The American army broke through at Saint-Lô.

definitions.definition: So as to pass a stage in a process and proceed to the next stage or level.
examples: The bill will be tabled tomorrow, but I doubt that it will be voted through .
She progressed through to the final round of the competition.

definitions.definition: From beginning to end, or from the present position to the end.
examples: Others went to bed for the night; he worked straight through .
The baby cried the whole night through .
He said he would see it through .

definitions.definition: Throughout something; all the way across or into.
examples: Leave the yarn in the dye overnight so the color soaks through .

definitions.definition: So as to connect or reach .
examples: I've been ringing my bank all day, and finally I've got through .
Can you put me through to the manager?
